  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The use of temporary stomas has been demonstrated to reduce septic complications after
      colorectal cancer surgery, especially in high-risk anastomosis; therefore, it is necessary to
      reduce the number of complications secondary to ostomy takedowns, namely wound infection. The
      aim of this study is to compare the rates of superficial wound infection, healing time and
      patient satisfaction after pursestring closure vs &quot;gunsight&quot; skin incision and closure
      technique closure.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
